The initial task in determining the natural response of the circuit depicted in Fig. 8.1 involves formulating the differential equation that governs the voltage $v$. We opt to determine the voltage initially, since it remains consistent across all components. Subsequently, we can identify the branch current by employing the current-voltage relationship specific to the branch component. We derive the differential equation for the voltage by summing the currents exiting the top node, expressing each current as a function of the unknown voltage $v$:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{v}{R}+\frac{1}{L} \int_{0}^{t} v d \tau+I_{0}+C \frac{d v}{d t}=0 \tag{8.1}
\end{equation*}
$$

By differentiating Equation 8.1 with respect to $t$ and considering that $I_{0}$ is a constant, we obtain:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{R} \frac{d v}{d t}+\frac{v}{L}+C \frac{d^{2} v}{d t^{2}}=0 \tag{8.2}
\end{equation*}
$$

Next, we divide Equation 8.2 by the capacitance $C$ and arrange the derivatives in descending order:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d^{2} v}{d t^{2}}+\frac{1}{R C} \frac{d v}{d t}+\frac{v}{L C}=0 \tag{8.3}
\end{equation*}
$$

Contrasting Equation 8.3 with the differential equations developed in Chapter 7, we observe a distinction due to the presence of the term involving the second derivative. Equation 8.3 represents an ordinary, second-order differential equation featuring constant coefficients. The circuits discussed in this chapter incorporate both inductors and capacitors, leading to a second-order differential equation describing these circuits. Consequently, we occasionally refer to such circuits as second-order circuits.

To address the General Solution of the Second-Order Differential Equation, we cannot solve Equation 8.3 by separating variables and integrating as we did with first-order equations in Chapter 7. Instead, we traditionally assume that the solution takes an exponential form, positing that the voltage can be expressed as:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=A e^{s t} \tag{8.4}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $A$ and $s$ are as yet undetermined constants. Prior to demonstrating how this assumption yields a solution to Equation 8.3, it's essential to justify the assumption. The most compelling argument in favor of Equation 8.4 is that, as indicated by Equation 8.3, the sum of the second derivative of the solution, a constant multiple of the first derivative, and a constant multiple of the solution itself must equal zero for all $t$. This condition is met only if higher-order derivatives of the solution mirror the solution's form, a characteristic exhibited by the exponential function. A further argument supporting Equation 8.4 is that all solutions to the first-order equations derived in Chapter 7 were exponential. It stands to reason that the solution to the second-order equation would also involve the exponential function.

For Equation 8.4 to be a valid solution of Equation 8.3, it must hold true for all $t$. Substituting Equation 8.4 into Equation 8.3 yields:

$$
A s^{2} e^{s t}+\frac{A s}{R C} e^{s t}+\frac{A e^{s t}}{L C}=0
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
A e^{s t}\left(s^{2}+\frac{s}{R C}+\frac{1}{L C}\right)=0 \tag{8.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

For this equation to hold for all $t$, $A$ must be zero or the expression in parentheses must be zero, since $e^{s t}$ is never zero for finite $s t$. The assumption of $A=0$ cannot serve as a general solution, as it implies a zero voltage across all time—a physically implausible scenario if energy is stored in either the inductor or capacitor. Thus, for Equation 8.4 to solve Equation 8.3, the expression in parentheses in Equation 8.5 must be zero, leading to:

$$
\begin{equation*}
s^{2}+\frac{s}{R C}+\frac{1}{L C}=0 \tag{8.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 8.6 is termed the characteristic equation of the differential equation, as its roots dictate the mathematical nature of $v(t)$.

The roots of Equation 8.6 are given by:

$$
\begin{align*}
& s_{1}=-\frac{1}{2 R C}+\sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{2 R C}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{L C}}  \tag{8.7}\\
& s_{2}=-\frac{1}{2 R C}-\sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{2 R C}\right)^{2}-\frac{1}{L C}} \tag{8.8}
\end{align*}
$$

Substituting either root into Equation 8.4 yields a solution that satisfies the differential equation, Equation 8.3. Note that this holds for any value of $A$. Therefore, both

$$
\begin{aligned}
& v=A_{1} e^{s_{1} t} \text { and } \\
& v=A_{2} e^{s_{2} t}
\end{aligned}
$$

are solutions to Equation 8.3. If we define these solutions as $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$, respectively, their sum is also a solution. Specifically, if we set

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=v_{1}+v_{2}=A_{1} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2} e^{s_{2} t} \tag{8.9}
\end{equation*}
$$

then

$$
\begin{align*}
\frac{d v}{d t} & =A_{1} s_{1} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2} s_{2} e^{s_{2} t}  \tag{8.10}\\
\frac{d^{2} v}{d t^{2}} & =A_{1} s_{1}^{2} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2} s_{2}^{2} e^{s_{2} t} \tag{8.11}
\end{align*}
$$

Inserting Equations 8.9-8.11 into Equation 8.3 results in:

$$
\begin{equation*}
A_{1} e^{s_{1} t}\left(s_{1}^{2}+\frac{1}{R C} s_{1}+\frac{1}{L C}\right)+A_{2} e^{s_{2} t}\left(s_{2}^{2}+\frac{1}{R C} s_{2}+\frac{1}{L C}\right)=0 \tag{8.12}
\end{equation*}
$$

However, each term in parentheses is zero by definition, as $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are roots of the characteristic equation. Hence, the natural response of the parallel $R L C$ circuit depicted in Fig. 8.1 assumes the form:

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=A_{1} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2} e^{s_{2} t} \tag{8.13}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 8.13 echoes the assumption made in Equation 8.9. We have established that $v_{1}$ is a solution, $v_{2}$ is a solution, and their sum, $v_{1}+v_{2}$, is also a solution. Thus, the general solution to Equation 8.3 follows the form stated in Equation 8.13. The roots of the characteristic equation ($s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$) are dictated by the circuit parameters $R, L$, and $C$. Initial conditions dictate the values of the constants $A_{1}$ and $A_{2}$. If the roots $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are equal, the form of Equation 8.13 must be altered, which we address in Section 8.2 when discussing the critically damped voltage response.

The behavior of $v(t)$ hinges on the values of $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$. Therefore, the initial step in ascertaining the natural response is to determine the roots of the characteristic equation. Referring back to Equations 8.7 and 8.8, we recast them using a notation prevalent in the literature:

$$
\begin{align*}
& s_{1}=-\alpha+\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-\omega_{0}^{2}}  \tag{8.14}\\
& s_{2}=-\alpha-\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-\omega_{0}^{2}} \tag{8.15}
\end{align*}
$$

where

Neper frequency, parallel RLC circuit

Resonant radian frequency, parallel RLC circuit

$$
\begin{equation*}
\alpha=\frac{1}{2 R C} \tag{8.16}
\end{equation*}
$$

$$
\begin{equation*}
\omega_{0}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{L C}} \tag{8.17}
\end{equation*}
$$

These findings are summarized in Table 8.1.

TABLE 8.1 Natural Response Parameters of the Parallel RLC Circuit

| Parameter | Terminology | Value In <br> Natural Response |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| $s_{1}, s_{2}$ | Characteristic roots | $s_{1}=-\alpha+\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-\omega_{0}^{2}}$ |
|  |  | $s_{2}=-\alpha-\sqrt{\alpha^{2}-\omega_{0}^{2}}$ |
| $\alpha$ | Neper frequency | $\alpha=\frac{1}{2 R C}$ |
| $\omega_{0}$ | Resonant radian frequency | $\omega_{0}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{L C}}$ |

Given that the exponent of $e$ must be dimensionless, both $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ (and by extension, $\alpha$ and $\omega_{0}$) must possess the dimensions of the reciprocal of time, or frequency. To differentiate among the frequencies $s_{1}, s_{2}, \alpha$, and $\omega_{0}$, we employ the following terminology: $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are termed complex frequencies, $\alpha$ is known as the neper frequency, and $\omega_{0}$ is identified as the resonant radian frequency. The significance of this terminology becomes clearer as we progress through subsequent chapters. All these frequencies are measured in radians per second ($\mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$). The nature of the roots $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ is contingent on the values of $\alpha$ and $\omega_{0}$. There are three potential scenarios. First, if $\omega_{0}^{2}<\alpha^{2}$, the roots will both be real and distinct, leading to an overdamped voltage response. Second, if $\omega_{0}^{2}>\alpha^{2}$, both $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ will be complex and conjugate, indicating an underdamped response. The third possibility is that $\omega_{0}^{2}=\alpha^{2}$, in which case $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ will be real and equal, characterizing a critically damped response. Damping influences how the voltage response attains its final (or steady-state) value, which we explore in Section 8.2 for each scenario.

Example 8.1 demonstrates how the numerical values of $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are determined by the values of $R, L$, and $C$.

#### Example 8.1 Determining the Roots of the Characteristic Equation for a Parallel RLC Circuit

a) Calculate the roots of the characteristic equation governing the transient behavior of the voltage depicted in Fig. 8.5 for $R=200 \Omega, L=50 \mathrm{mH}$, and $C=0.2 \mu \mathrm{~F}$.
b) Determine whether the response will be overdamped, underdamped, or critically damped.
c) Repeat (a) and (b) for $R=312.5 \Omega$.
d) Identify the value of $R$ that results in a critically damped response.

Figure 8.5 depicts a parallel RLC circuit utilized to analyze the natural response of the system.

#### Solution

a) For the specified values of $R, L$, and $C$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha & =\frac{1}{2 R C}=\frac{10^{6}}{(400)(0.2)}=1.25 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
\omega_{0}^{2} & =\frac{1}{L C}=\frac{\left(10^{3}\right)\left(10^{6}\right)}{(50)(0.2)}=10^{8} \mathrm{rad}^{2} / \mathrm{s}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Using Equations 8.14 and 8.15,

$$
\begin{aligned}
s_{1} & =-1.25 \times 10^{4}+\sqrt{1.5625 \times 10^{8}-10^{8}} \\
& =-12,500+7500=-5000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
s_{2} & =-1.25 \times 10^{4}-\sqrt{1.5625 \times 10^{8}-10^{8}}
\end{aligned}
$$

b) The voltage response is overdamped since $\omega_{0}^{2}<\alpha^{2}$.
c) For $R=312.5 \Omega$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\alpha & =\frac{10^{6}}{(625)(0.2)}=8000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
\alpha^{2} & =64 \times 10^{6}=0.64 \times 10^{8} \mathrm{rad}^{2} / \mathrm{s}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

With $\omega_{0}^{2}$ unchanged at $10^{8} \mathrm{rad}^{2} / \mathrm{s}^{2}$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& s_{1}=-8000+j 6000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
& s_{2}=-8000-j 6000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

In this instance, the voltage response is underdamped because $\omega_{0}^{2}>\alpha^{2}$.
d) For critical damping, $\alpha^{2}=\omega_{0}^{2}$, hence

$$
\left(\frac{1}{2 R C}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{L C}=10^{8}
$$

or

$$
\frac{1}{2 R C}=10^{4}
$$

and

$$
R=\frac{10^{6}}{\left(2 \times 10^{4}\right)(0.2)}=250 \Omega
$$

ASSESSMENT PROBLEM

Objective 1—Be able to determine the natural response and the step response of parallel RLC circuits
8.1 The resistance and inductance of the circuit in Fig. 8.5 are $100 \Omega$ and 20 mH , respectively.
a) Find the value of $C$ that results in a critically damped voltage response.
b) If $C$ is adjusted to yield a neper frequency of $5 \mathrm{krad} / \mathrm{s}$, determine the value of $C$ and the roots of the characteristic equation.
c) If $C$ is adjusted to yield a resonant frequency of $20 \mathrm{krad} / \mathrm{s}$, determine the value of $C$ and the roots of the characteristic equation.

Answer: (a) 500 nF ;
(b) $C=1 \mu \mathrm{~F}$, $s_{1}=-5000+j 5000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$, $s_{2}=-5000-j 5000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} ;$
(c) $C=125 \mathrm{nF}$,
$s_{1}=-5359 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$,
$s_{2}=-74,641 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$.

