The exponent of $e$ must be dimensionless, implying that $s_{1}$, $s_{2}$ (and by extension, $\alpha$ and $\omega_{0}$) must be dimensionally equivalent to frequency. To differentiate among $s_{1}$, $s_{2}$, $\alpha$, and $\omega_{0}$, we use specific terminology: $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are termed complex frequencies, $\alpha$ is the neper frequency, and $\omega_{0}$ is the resonant radian frequency. The implications of this terminology will become clearer as we progress through subsequent chapters. All these frequencies are measured in radians per second ($\mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$). The nature of the roots $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ depends on $\alpha$ and $\omega_{0}$, leading to three potential scenarios. If $\omega_{0}^{2}<\alpha^{2}$, both roots are real and distinct, indicating an overdamped voltage response. If $\omega_{0}^{2}>\alpha^{2}$, $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are complex conjugates, suggesting an underdamped response. Lastly, when $\omega_{0}^{2}=\alpha^{2}$, $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ are real and equal, corresponding to a critically damped response. The damping influences how the voltage response approaches its final value, a topic we'll explore further in Section 8.2.

