Finding the step response of a parallel $R L C$ circuit requires determining the voltage across the parallel branches or the current in the separate branches due to the abrupt application of a direct current source. The circuit may or may not contain stored energy upon the application of the current source. The associated task is illustrated in Figure 8.11. To establish a general method for calculating the step response of a second-order circuit, we concentrate on determining the current through the inductive branch ($i_{L}$). This current is significant because it does not decay to zero as time ($t$) progresses. Eventually, after the switch has been open for a considerable duration, the inductor current becomes equal to the direct current source current ($I$). In order to concentrate on the method for determining the step response, we assume that the circuit starts with zero stored energy. This assumption streamlines the calculations without altering the fundamental process. We will see in Example 8.10 how the presence of initially stored energy affects the general procedure.

To determine the inductor current ($i_{L}$), one must solve a second-order differential equation set equal to the forcing function ($I$), which we derive as follows. According to Kirchhoff's current law, we have

$$
i_{L}+i_{R}+i_{C}=I
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{L}+\frac{v}{R}+C \frac{d v}{d t}=I \tag{8.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

Since

$$
\begin{equation*}
v=L \frac{d i_{L}}{d t} \tag{8.38}
\end{equation*}
$$

we obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d v}{d t}=L \frac{d^{2} i_{L}}{d t^{2}} \tag{8.39}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting Eqs. 8.38 and 8.39 into Eq. 8.37 yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{L}+\frac{L}{R} \frac{d i_{L}}{d t}+L C \frac{d^{2} i_{L}}{d t^{2}}=I \tag{8.40}
\end{equation*}
$$

To facilitate calculations, we divide the equation by $L C$ and reorganize the terms:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d^{2} i_{L}}{d t^{2}}+\frac{1}{R C} \frac{d i_{L}}{d t}+\frac{i_{L}}{L C}=\frac{I}{L C} \tag{8.41}
\end{equation*}
$$

Comparing Eq. 8.41 with Eq. 8.3 demonstrates that the presence of a non-zero term on the right-hand side of the equation changes the nature of the task. Before presenting the direct method for solving Eq. 8.41, we obtain the solution indirectly. Once we know the solution to Eq. 8.41, explaining the direct method will be more straightforward.

The Indirect Method

We can find $i_{L}$ indirectly by first calculating the voltage ($v$). We do this using the techniques introduced in Section 8.2, as the differential equation that $v$ must satisfy is identical to Eq. 8.3. To see this, we simply return to Eq. 8.37 and express $i_{L}$ in terms of $v$; hence

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1}{L} \int_{0}^{t} v d \tau+\frac{v}{R}+C \frac{d v}{d t}=I \tag{8.42}
\end{equation*}
$$

Differentiating Eq. 8.42 with respect to $t$ once eliminates the right-hand side because $I$ is constant. Therefore

$$
\frac{v}{L}+\frac{1}{R} \frac{d v}{d t}+C \frac{d^{2} v}{d t^{2}}=0
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d^{2} v}{d t^{2}}+\frac{1}{R C} \frac{d v}{d t}+\frac{v}{L C}=0 \tag{8.43}
\end{equation*}
$$

As discussed in Section 8.2, the solution for $v$ depends on the roots of the characteristic equation. Therefore, the three possible solutions are

$$
\begin{align*}
& v=A_{1} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2} e^{s_{2} t}  \tag{8.44}\\
& v=B_{1} e^{-\alpha t} \cos \omega_{d} t+B_{2} e^{-\alpha t} \sin \omega_{d} t  \tag{8.45}\\
& v=D_{1} t e^{-\alpha t}+D_{2} e^{-\alpha t} \tag{8.46}
\end{align*}
$$

A note of caution: Due to the presence of a source in the circuit after $t>0$, you must consider the source current's value at $t=0^{+}$ when evaluating the coefficients in Eqs. 8.44-8.46.

To find the three possible solutions for $i_{L}$, we substitute Eqs. 8.44-8.46 into Eq. 8.37. You should be able to verify that the three solutions for $i_{L}$ will be

$$
\begin{align*}
& i_{L}=I+A_{1}^{\prime} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2}^{\prime} e^{s_{2} t}  \tag{8.47}\\
& i_{L}=I+B_{1}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \cos \omega_{d} t+B_{2}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \sin \omega_{d} t  \tag{8.48}\\
& i_{L}=I+D_{1}^{\prime} t e^{-\alpha t}+D_{2}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \tag{8.49}
\end{align*}
$$

where $A_{1}^{\prime}, A_{2}^{\prime}, B_{1}^{\prime}, B_{2}^{\prime}, D_{1}^{\prime}$, and $D_{2}^{\prime}$ are arbitrary constants. In each case, the primed constants can be found indirectly in terms of the arbitrary constants associated with the voltage solution, although this method is complicated.

The Direct Method

Finding the primed constants directly in relation to the initial values of the response function is much easier. For the circuit being considered, we determine the primed constants from $i_{L}(0)$ and $\frac{d i_{L}}{d t}(0)$.

The solution for a second-order differential equation with a constant forcing function is the sum of the forced response and a response function identical in form to the natural response. Therefore, we can always express the solution for the step response in the form

$$
i=I_{f}+\left\{\begin{array}{c}
\text { function of the same form }  \tag{8.50}\\
\text { as the natural response }
\end{array}\right\}
$$

or

$$
v=V_{f}+\left\{\begin{array}{r}
\text { function of the same form }  \tag{8.51}\\
\text { as the natural response }
\end{array}\right\}
$$

where $I_{f}$ and $V_{f}$ denote the final value of the response function. The final value may be zero, as was the case with the voltage $v$ in the circuit depicted in Figure 8.8.

Examples 8.6-8.10 demonstrate the technique of finding the step response of a parallel $R L C$ circuit using the direct method.

