#### Solution

a) With no energy stored in the circuit before the application of the dc current source, the initial current in the inductor is zero. The inductor prevents an instantaneous change in inductor current; thus $i_{L}(0)=0$ immediately after the switch is opened.
b) The initial voltage across the capacitor is zero before the switch is opened; hence it remains zero immediately after. Now, because $v=L d i_{L} / d t$,

$$
\frac{d i_{L}}{d t}\left(0^{+}\right)=0
$$

c) From the circuit elements, we calculate

$$
\begin{aligned}
\omega_{0}^{2} & =\frac{1}{L C}=\frac{10^{12}}{(25)(25)}=16 \times 10^{8} \\
\alpha & =\frac{1}{2 R C}=\frac{10^{9}}{(2)(400)(25)}=5 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

or

$$
\alpha^{2}=25 \times 10^{8}
$$

Since $\omega_{0}^{2}<\alpha^{2}$, the roots of the characteristic equation are real and distinct. Therefore

$$
\begin{aligned}
& s_{1}=-5 \times 10^{4}+3 \times 10^{4}=-20,000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
& s_{2}=-5 \times 10^{4}-3 \times 10^{4}=-80,000 \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

d) As the roots of the characteristic equation are real and distinct, the inductor current response will be overdamped. Thus $i_{L}(t)$ takes the form of Eq. 8.47, which is

$$
i_{L}=I_{f}+A_{1}^{\prime} e^{s_{1} t}+A_{2}^{\prime} e^{s_{2} t}
$$
Inductor current in overdamped parallel RLC circuit step response

From this solution, the two simultaneous equations that determine $A_{1}^{\prime}$ and $A_{2}^{\prime}$ are

$$
\begin{aligned}
i_{L}(0) & =I_{f}+A_{1}^{\prime}+A_{2}^{\prime}=0 \\
\frac{d i_{L}}{d t}(0) & =s_{1} A_{1}^{\prime}+s_{2} A_{2}^{\prime}=0
\end{aligned}
$$

Solving for $A_{1}^{\prime}$ and $A_{2}^{\prime}$ gives

$$
A_{1}^{\prime}=-32 \mathrm{~mA} \quad \text { and } \quad A_{2}^{\prime}=8 \mathrm{~mA}
$$

The numerical solution for $i_{L}(t)$ is

$$
i_{L}(t)=\left(24-32 e^{-20,000 t}+8 e^{-80,000 t}\right) \mathrm{mA}, \quad t \geq 0
$$

#### Example 8.7: Finding the Underdamped Step Response of a Parallel RLC Circuit

The resistor in the circuit from Example 8.6 (Fig. 8.12) is increased to $625 \Omega$. Find $i_{L}(t)$ for $t \geq 0$.

#### Solution

With $L$ and $C$ unchanged, $\omega_{0}^{2}$ retains the same value as in Example 8.6; that is, $\omega_{0}^{2}=16 \times 10^{8}$. Increasing $R$ to $625 \Omega$ reduces $\alpha$ to $3.2 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}$. Since $\omega_{0}^{2}>\alpha^{2}$, the roots of the characteristic equation are complex. Thus

$$
\begin{aligned}
& s_{1}=-3.2 \times 10^{4}+j 2.4 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \\
& s_{2}=-3.2 \times 10^{4}-j 2.4 \times 10^{4} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s}
\end{aligned}
$$

The current response is now underdamped and follows Eq. 8.48:

$$
i_{L}(t)=I_{f}+B_{1}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \cos \omega_{d} t+B_{2}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \sin \omega_{d} t
$$

