The methods for determining the natural or step responses of a series $R L C$ circuit are analogous to those used for a parallel $R L C$ circuit, since both configurations are governed by differential equations of identical structure. The process commences by calculating the voltage sums around the closed loop of the circuit depicted in Fig. 8.14, leading to

$$
\begin{equation*}
R i + L \frac{d i}{d t} + \frac{1}{C} \int_{0}^{t} i d \tau + V_{0} = 0 \tag{8.52}
\end{equation*}
$$

Differentiating equation 8.52 once with respect to $t$ yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
R \frac{d i}{d t} + L \frac{d^{2} i}{d t^{2}} + \frac{i}{C} = 0 \tag{8.53}
\end{equation*}
$$

The series RLC circuit in Figure 8.14 is used to demonstrate the natural response, while Figure 8.15 illustrates the step response circuit, which includes a voltage source $V$, a switch $SW1$, a resistor $R$, an inductor $L$, and a capacitor $C$. The circuit models the transient behavior when the switch is closed at $t=0$.

By rearranging the differentiated equation, we obtain

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d^{2} i}{d t^{2}} + \frac{R}{L} \frac{d i}{d t} + \frac{i}{L C} = 0 \tag{8.54}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 8.54 shares the same structure as equation 8.3. Thus, we employ the same methodology to solve equation 8.54 as we did for equation 8.3.

For the series $R L C$ circuit, the characteristic equation is

$$
\begin{equation*}
s^{2} + \frac{R}{L} s + \frac{1}{L C} = 0 \tag{8.55}
\end{equation*}
$$

with roots

$$
\begin{equation*}
s_{1,2} = -\frac{R}{2 L} \pm \sqrt{\left(\frac{R}{2 L}\right)^{2} - \frac{1}{L C}} \tag{8.56}
\end{equation*}
$$

or

$$
\begin{equation*}
s_{1,2} = -\alpha \pm \sqrt{\alpha^{2} - \omega_{0}^{2}} \tag{8.57}
\end{equation*}
$$

The neper frequency $(\alpha)$ for the series $R L C$ circuit is

$$
\begin{equation*}
\alpha = \frac{R}{2 L} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \tag{8.58}
\end{equation*}
$$

and the resonant radian frequency is

$$
\begin{equation*}
\omega_{0} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{L C}} \mathrm{rad} / \mathrm{s} \tag{8.59}
\end{equation*}
$$

The neper frequency equation for the series $R L C$ circuit differs from that of the parallel $R L C$ circuit, but the equations for resonant and damped radian frequencies are identical.

The current response may be overdamped, underdamped, or critically damped depending on whether $\omega_{0}^{2} < \alpha^{2}$, $\omega_{0}^{2} > \alpha^{2}$, or $\omega_{0}^{2} = \alpha^{2}$. Consequently, the three possible solutions for the current are:

$$
\begin{align*}
& i(t) = A_{1} e^{s_{1} t} + A_{2} e^{s_{2} t} \text{ (overdamped)} \tag{8.60} \\
& i(t) = B_{1} e^{-\alpha t} \cos \omega_{d} t + B_{2} e^{-\alpha t} \sin \omega_{d} t \text{ (underdamped)} \tag{8.61} \\
& i(t) = D_{1} t e^{-\alpha t} + D_{2} e^{-\alpha t} \text{ (critically damped)} \tag{8.62}
\end{align*}
$$

After determining the natural current response, the natural voltage response across any circuit element can be found.

To confirm that the method for finding the step response of a series $R L C$ circuit is consistent with that of a parallel $R L C$ circuit, we demonstrate that the differential equation describing the capacitor voltage in Fig. 8.15 has the same form as the equation describing the inductor current in Fig. 8.11. Assuming no initial energy storage in the circuit, applying Kirchhoff's voltage law to the circuit in Fig. 8.15 results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
V = R i + L \frac{d i}{d t} + v_{C} \tag{8.63}
\end{equation*}
$$

The current $(i)$ is related to the capacitor voltage $(v_{C})$ by

$$
\begin{equation*}
i = C \frac{d v_{C}}{d t} \tag{8.64}
\end{equation*}
$$

Differentiating this with respect to $t$ gives

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d i}{d t} = C \frac{d^{2} v_{C}}{d t^{2}} \tag{8.65}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting equations 8.64 and 8.65 into equation 8.63 yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
\frac{d^{2} v_{C}}{d t^{2}} + \frac{R}{L} \frac{d v_{C}}{d t} + \frac{v_{C}}{L C} = \frac{V}{L C} \tag{8.66}
\end{equation*}
$$

Equation 8.66 is identical in form to equation 8.41, implying that the process for determining $v_{C}$ mirrors that for finding $i_{L}$. The three possible solutions for $v_{C}$ are:

$$
\begin{align*}
& v_{C} = V_{f} + A_{1}^{\prime} e^{s_{1} t} + A_{2}^{\prime} e^{s_{2} t} \text{ (overdamped)} \tag{8.67} \\
& v_{C} = V_{f} + B_{1}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \cos \omega_{d} t + B_{2}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \sin \omega_{d} t \text{ (underdamped)} \tag{8.68} \\
& v_{C} = V_{f} + D_{1}^{\prime} t e^{-\alpha t} + D_{2}^{\prime} e^{-\alpha t} \text{ (critically damped)} \tag{8.69}
\end{align*}
$$

where $V_{f}$ is the final value of $v_{C}$, which corresponds to the dc source voltage $V$.

Examples 8.11 and 8.12 demonstrate the process of finding the natural and step responses of a series $R L C$ circuit.

Example 8.11 focuses on the underdamped natural response of a series RLC circuit. A $0.1 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ capacitor charged to 100 V is discharged through a series combination of a 100 mH inductor and a $560 \Omega$ resistor at $t=0$. The solution involves calculating the characteristic equation's roots and applying initial conditions to determine the constants in the solution for $i(t)$ and $v_{C}(t)$.

Example 8.12 addresses the underdamped step response of a series RLC circuit with an initial condition of zero energy stored in the inductor and capacitor. The solution again involves finding the characteristic equation's roots and applying initial conditions to find the constants in the solution for $v_{C}(t)$.

The assessment problems 8.7 and 8.8 involve finding transient responses of current and voltage across components in a series RLC circuit after a switch is moved from one position to another at $t=0$. Solutions are provided for these problems, demonstrating the application of the concepts discussed.
